         <div type="entry">
                <head>Isḥoq Ṣaliba</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Ishoq-Saliba</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/295</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">286</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="217-218"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/558</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Last <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Dayro d-Mor Abay.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(d. 1730) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Last <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Dayro d-Mor Abay. Little is known about his early life. He may
                        have been from Qilleth and may have joined <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Matay-Dayro-d-Mor">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/227">Dayro d-Mor
                            Matay</persName>
                        </ref>. He was consecrated <abbr>bp.</abbr> of Dayro d-Mor Abay with the unusual
                        Syriac, rather than Greek, honorific title Isḥoq. He may have participated
                        in the installation of the anti-patriarch Shemʿun of Maʿdan <abbr>ca.</abbr> 1699. After
                        his death in 1730, the diocese of Mor Abay, which then included Ṣawro,
                        Qilleth, and its villages, Bafawah, ʿWein, Kharbah and Maʿsarteh, became
                        part of the diocese of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Mardin">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/130">Mardin</placeName>
                        </ref>.</p>
                </div>
